The '''Founder's Pie Calculator''' is a tool for distributing [[Share (finance)|shares]] when starting a [[business venture]]. It was first described in an article by Frank Demmler, who is an Adjunct Teaching Professor of Entrepreneurship at [[Carnegie Mellon University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tepper.cmu.edu/our-faculty-and-research/about-our-faculty/faculty-profiles/fd0n/demmler-l|title=L. Frank Demmler|website=Tepper School of Business|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrew.cmu.edu/user/fd0n/index.html|title=Frank Demmler's Home Page|last=|first=|date=|website=www.andrew.cmu.edu|publisher=|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>

In contrast to popular notion, the shares are not distributed equally (because "it's fair") but using a system of 5 important aspects of any business venture, assigning a relative weight to them and then rating the founders in each of these aspects.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrew.cmu.edu/user/fd0n/35%20Founders'%20Pie%20Calculator.htm|title=Cutting Up the Founder’s Pie|website=www.andrew.cmu.edu|access-date=2016-11-14}}</ref>

