'''Johann Urban''' (or '''Johannes Urban''',{{sfn|Fünfundzwanzig Jahre Erste Österreichische Glanzstoff-Fabrik}} 7 June 1863 – 13 November 1940) was an Austrian chemist and industrialist. He was one of the pioneers of the artificial silk industry.

==Early years==
Johann Urban was born on 7 June 1863 in Wuchern near Marburg (now [[Maribor]]), [[Lower Styria]].
His father was a timber merchant.{{sfn|Büttner|1972}}
He studied mechanical and electrical engineering in [[Graz]], and expected to work as a teacher at a state vocational school.{{sfn|Wieninger|2002|pp=374–375}}
Instead, he found work in a light bulb factory in [[Rotterdam]], where he met [[Max Fremery]].{{sfn|Büttner|1972}}
In the mid-1880s Urban and Fremery took over the technical management of a light bulb factory in [[Gelnhausen]].{{sfn|Beau|1961|pp=400ff}}

==Lamp manufacture (1885–1900)==
The Swiss chemist [[Matthias Eduard Schweizer]] (1818–60) had found in 1857 that cotton could be dissolved in a solution of copper salts and ammonia and then regenerated.{{sfn|Woodings|2001|p=4}}
In 1890 the French chemist Louis Henri Despeissis invented the [[cuprammonium]] process for spinning fibers from  cotton dissolved in [[Schweizer's reagent]].{{sfn|Woodings|2001|p=4}}
Despeissis died in 1892 and his patent was not renewed.{{sfn|Woodings|2001|p=5}}
In 1891 Fremery and Urban adapted the Despaissis process to make electric lamp filaments from carbon fiber.{{sfn|Morgan|2005|p=149}}
In 1892 they founded an incandescent electric lamp manufacturing company, ''Rheinische Glühlampenfabrik'' in [[Oberbruch Industry Park|Oberbruch]], in the [[Heinsberg]] district.{{sfn|Heerding|1988|p=37}}
In 1895 the factory employed 36 men and 46 women, and was producing about 400,000 lamps per year.{{sfn|Heerding|1988|p=37}}
By 1900 the company had 350 employees, but was struggling to remain profitable in the face of the low prices of the major electrical manufacturers.{{sfn|Heerding|1988|p=63}}

==Rayon manufacture (1898–1912)==

Fremery and Urban became involved in developing synthetic fiber (''Glanzstoff'') in the mid-1890s.{{sfn|Beau|1961|pp=400ff}}
The success of the [[nitrocellulose]] fiber developed by [[Hilaire de Chardonnet]] encouraged Fremery and Urban to investigate making artificial silk, which they named "Silkimit" and patented in 1897.
Their cuprammonium process was cheaper and safer than nitrocellulose.{{sfn|Morgan|2005|p=149}}
The company had developed a process by 1897 that used rotating cylinders to stretch the fibers into finer filaments that could be used for making clothes.{{sfn|Woodings|2001|p=91}}
They patented a version of the Despeissis process with the addition of a practical method for spinning the fiber.{{sfn|Woodings|2001|p=5}}
In Oberbruch in 1898 they established the first factory in Germany to economically produce artificial fiber, using a patent for manufacture of rayon made from cellulose in a copper-ammonia solution.
The workforce had grown to 700 people within one year.{{sfn|Beau|1961|pp=400ff}}

Fremery and Urban moved their headquarters to [[Elberfeld]], now a suburb of [[Wuppertal]].{{sfn|Kleinschmidt|2002|loc=PT210}}
[[Vereinigte Glanzstoff-Fabriken]] (VGF) was launched on 19 September 1899 with 2 million marks of capital.
The Bergisch-Märkischen bank provided the financing.{{sfn|Woodings|2001|p=94}}
Urban became the technical director of the newly founded VGF.{{sfn|Wieninger|2002|pp=374–375}}
Fremery and Urban, with the Alsatian textile chemist David Emil Bronnert (1868–1928), took out two more basic patents in 1900.{{sfn|Woodings|2001|p=94}}
From 1904 Urban was head of the ''Erste österreichische Glanzstoff-Fabriken'' (First Austrian Rayon Factory) in [[Sankt Pölten]].{{sfn|Wieninger|2002|pp=374–375}}
This was a joint venture of several German and Austrian firms, led by VGF.
It grew rapidly, and by 1913 employed about 1,700 people.{{sfn|Matis|1994|p=399}}

Johann Urban died on 13 November 1940 in Vienna.{{sfn|Wieninger|2002|pp=374–375}}

