{{other people||William Lucas (disambiguation)}} [[File:WilliamLucasVA.jpg|thumb|William Lucas]] '''William Lucas''' (November 30, 1800 &ndash; August 29, 1877) was a nineteenth-century politician and lawyer from [[Virginia]].
==Early life== Born at "[[Cold Spring (Shepherdstown, West Virginia)|Cold Spring]]" near [[Shepherdstown, West Virginia|Shepherdstown, Virginia]] (now [[West Virginia]]) in 1800 Lucas was the brother of [[Edward Lucas (congressman)|Edward Lucas]]. Lucas attended the village schools and Jefferson College at Gettysburg, Pennsylvania.<ref>[[#pulliam|Pulliam 1901, p. 108]]</ref> He went on to graduate from Tucker Law School in 1825, being admitted to the bar the same year.<ref>[[#bioguide|Congressional Biographical Directory, "William Lucas"]]</ref>
==Career== He commenced practice in Shepherdstown before moving to [[Charles Town, West Virginia|Charles Town, Virginia]] (now [[West Virginia]]) in 1830 and continued practice there as well as engaging in horticultural pursuits.<ref>[[#bioguide|Congressional Biographical Directory, "William Lucas"]]</ref>
Lucas was a member of the [[Virginia House of Delegates]] in 1838 and 1839 and was elected a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[United States House of Representatives]] in 1838, serving from 1839 to 1841 and being unsuccessful for reelection in 1840. He was elected back to the House in 1842, serving again from 1843 to 1845 and once again being unsuccessful for reelection in 1844.<ref>[[#bioguide|Congressional Biographical Directory, "William Lucas"]]</ref>
Afterwards, Lucas resumed practicing law and engagements in horticultural pursuits and was a delegate to the [[Virginia Constitutional Convention of 1850|Virginia Constitutional Convention]] in 1850 and 1851. He was one of four delegates elected from the northern Valley delegate district made up of his home district of Jefferson County as well as Berkeley and Clarke Counties.<ref>[[#pulliam|Pulliam 1901, p. 99]]</ref>
==Death== He died at his estate called "[[Rion Hall]]" in [[Jefferson County, West Virginia]] on August 29, 1877 and was interred in Zion Episcopal Churchyard in [[Charles Town, West Virginia]].<ref>[[#bioguide|Congressional Biographical Directory, "William Lucas"]]</ref>
